<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="262" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,1483,1907]" pageId="9" pageNumber="262">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,269,1628,1654]" pageId="9" pageNumber="262">Remarks:</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Amaoka, K." box="[278,494,1628,1654]" pageId="9" pageNumber="262" pagination="65 - 340" refId="ref9705" refString="Amaoka, K. (1969) Studies on the sinistral flounders found in the waters around Japan. Taxonomy, anatomy and phylogeny. Journal of the Shimonoseki University of Fisheries, 18 (2), 65 - 340. [1 - 276]" type="journal article" year="1969">Amaoka (1969: 98</bibRefCitation>
[33]) synonymized 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schmidt" authorityYear="1931" box="[730,965,1628,1654]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Bothidae" genus="Arnoglossus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Pleuronectiformes" pageId="9" pageNumber="262" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="wakiyai">
<emphasis box="[730,965,1628,1654]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="262">Arnoglossus wakiyai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with 
<taxonomicName box="[1035,1404,1628,1654]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Paralichthyidae" genus="Pseudorhombus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Pleuronectiformes" pageId="9" pageNumber="262" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pentophthalmus">
<emphasis box="[1035,1404,1628,1654]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="262">Pseudorhombus pentophthalmus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in terms of the original description and drawing. Closer examination allows us to identify this specimen as 
<taxonomicName authority="Weber, 1913" authorityName="Weber" authorityYear="1913" box="[227,625,1700,1726]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Paralichthyidae" genus="Pseudorhombus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Pleuronectiformes" pageId="9" pageNumber="262" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="argus">
<emphasis box="[227,477,1700,1726]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="262">Pseudorhombus argus</emphasis>
Weber, 1913
</taxonomicName>
on the basis of the following characters: ctenoid scales on eyed side and cycloid scales on blind side; anterior dorsal-fin rays not prolonged, not entirely free from fin membrane; a line connecting base of first dorsal-fin ray and posterior nostril on eyed side crosses maxilla; origin of dorsal fin slightly in front of anterior edge of upper eye and just above posterior nostril on blind side; gill rakers slender, pointed and long, 15 on lower limb of first gill arch; maxilla extending only to below middle of lower eye. Pigmentation of specimen faded on both sides.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
